Treatment of early Squamous Cell Carcinoma (Cancer Eye) lesion in a mature cow. This form of neoplasia can be highly malignant and progress quickly. Lessons can be found on the palpebra (eyelids), third eyelids, or on the eye itself. Lesions found on the eye most commonly are found on the limbus which is junction between the sclera and corner (where the white of the eye meets the clear part). These lesions are often noted as a small white raised wart like lesion which can progress into more aggressive forms of the neoplasia in time. Treatment of these lesions can seem to halt progression. The technique used here uses a retrobulbar local anesthetic using a 3‚Äù spinal needle introduced behind the eye, manual proptosis of the globe, debunking of the lesion with a scalpel and cryotherapy or freezing of the affected area (3 freeze thaw cycles) to help reduce chance of reoccurrence. Unfortunately this condition has a genetic heritable predisposition and use of calves from these dams should be not used as replacements.
